---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="The Commander Variant">
  <main class="design-essay">
    
    <header class="essay-header">
      <span class="super-title">Design Philosophy II</span>
      <h1>A Commander Variant</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Familiar Language with Set Expectations</p>
    </header>

    <hr />

    <article class="prose-block">
      <p class="lead-paragraph">
        Tiny Leaders Reborn is, at its core, a Commander-variant format. Decks are built around a commander, 
        obey color identity, use the command zone, and follow singleton construction. If you already speak 
        the language of Commander, the structure will feel immediately recognizable, but every element has 
        been refined for deliberate, 1-v-1 play.
      </p>
    </article>

    <section class="chapter-section">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>From Pastime to Purpose</h3>
        <p>
          Where the original Tiny Leaders emerged as a way to pass the time between multiplayer pods, 
          TLR is built with a clearer purpose. Shaped by competitive 1v1 play in the French Magic community, 
          the format emphasizes tempo, sequencing, and meaningful interaction from the opening turn onward.
        </p>
        <p>
          The smaller scale naturally rewards tight decision-making, and while later design elements help 
          support competitive strategies, they are deliberately framed as options, rather than obligations.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="chapter-section alt-bg">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>A Spectrum of Expression</h3>
        <p>
          That flexibility is central to the formatâ€™s identity. TLR supports the full spectrum of Commander 
          expression, such as focused strategies, offbeat themes, and experimental builds. You can register 
          a finely tuned list or sit down with a concept-driven deck and expect the structure of the format 
          to meet you where you are. The format offers plenty of strategic depth but an equal amount of creativity.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="chapter-section">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h3>The Gravitational Center</h3>
        <p>
          Your commander remains the gravitational center of the deck. It defines your colors, informs your 
          strategy, and gives your list its identity, just as it does in traditional Commander. The difference 
          is immediacy and inevitability.
        </p>
        
        <div class="callout-box">
          <p>
            With fewer cards and faster games, your commander matters sooner and more often, as it anchors 
            your plan from the very beginning. Decisions come faster, stakes rise earlier, and the room for 
            clever lines and surprise interactions remains intact.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <footer class="essay-footer prose-block">
      <p>
        By preserving the Commander framework while refining it for 1v1 play, Tiny Leaders Reborn strikes 
        a careful balance of being familiar without being derivative, while at the same time, competitive 
        without being restrictive. The result is a format that welcomes Commander players through familiarity.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>TLR offers a tighter, more intentional battlefield where every mana and every turn matters.</strong>
      </p>
    </footer>

    <nav class="series-nav">
      
      <a href="/design/rule-of-three" class="nav-card prev">
        <span class="nav-label">Previous</span>
        <div class="nav-inner">
          <span class="nav-arrow">&larr;</span>
          <span class="chapter-title">The Rule of 3</span>
        </div>
      </a>

      <a href="/design/one-v-one" class="nav-card next">
        <span class="nav-label">Next Element</span>
        <div class="nav-inner">
          <span class="chapter-title">1v1 Structure</span>
          <span class="nav-arrow">&rarr;</span>
        </div>
      </a>

    </nav>

  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* --- REUSING DESIGN SYSTEM STYLES --- */
  .design-essay {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 3rem 1rem;
    color: var(--text-body);
  }

  .prose-block {
    max-width: 65ch;
    margin: 0 auto;
    line-height: 1.8;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
  }

  /* --- HEADER --- */
  .essay-header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .super-title {
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-weight: bold;
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .essay-header h1 {
    font-size: 3rem;
    color: var(--heading-color);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    line-height: 1.1;
  }

  .subtitle {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .lead-paragraph {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--heading-color);
  }

  /* --- SECTIONS --- */
  .chapter-section {
    padding: 3rem 0;
  }

  .chapter-section h3 {
    font-size: 1.75rem;
    color: var(--heading-color);
    margin-top: 0;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  /* --- CALLOUT BOX --- */
  .callout-box {
    background-color: var(--surface);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 1.5rem 2rem;
    margin: 2rem 0;
    font-style: italic;
    border-radius: 0 4px 4px 0;
  }

  .callout-box p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
  }

  /* --- ALT BACKGROUND --- */
  .alt-bg {
    background-color: var(--surface); /* Very subtle grey/off-white background */
    margin-left: calc(-50vw + 50%); /* Break out of container to full width */
    margin-right: calc(-50vw + 50%);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    padding-right: 1rem;
    width: 100vw;
  }

  /* --- SERIES NAVIGATION --- */
  .series-nav {
    margin-top: 6rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between; /* Pushes buttons to edges */
    align-items: flex-end; /* Aligns them to bottom if heights differ */
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  /* Shared Card Styles */
  .nav-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    text-decoration: none;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 300px;
    padding: 1rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 1px solid transparent; /* Invisible border by default */
    transition: all 0.2s ease;
  }

  .nav-card:hover {
    background-color: var(--surface);
    border-color: var(--border-subtle);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  /* Internal Layout */
  .nav-inner {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }

  /* Left/Right Specifics */
  .prev {
    align-items: flex-start; /* Aligns content to left */
    text-align: left;
  }

  .next {
    align-items: flex-end; /* Aligns content to right */
    text-align: right;
  }
  
  /* Flex direction row-reverse for Previous to keep arrow on outside? 
     No, standard "Arrow Title" is fine for prev. */

  .nav-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    font-weight: bold;
  }

  .chapter-title {
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: bold;
    color: var(--heading-color);
  }

  .nav-arrow {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  /* Mobile: Stack them vertically */
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .series-nav {
      flex-direction: column-reverse; /* Next on top, Prev on bottom usually better? Or standard flow */
      flex-direction: column; 
      gap: 2rem;
    }
    
    .nav-card {
      max-width: 100%;
      align-items: center; /* Center them on mobile */
      text-align: center;
      background-color: var(--surface);
      border-color: var(--border-subtle);
    }
    
    .prev, .next { align-items: center; text-align: center; }
  }
</style>